http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: GA's Features of Interest. FOIs are features (so a representation of a real-world object) that carry properties which are observed. FOIs can be either domain features (aka sampled features), e.g. 'Murray River', or a sampling feature, e.g. 'water gauge X' at the Murray River. GA's list of FOIs are derived from GA's internal databases that contain many thousands of features of interest to GA. Samples within GA's main systems are alsways associated with FOIs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: All the Concepts in this vocabulary

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A generic term for any hole or shaft drilled into the Earth. A borehole may have many purposes (eg, petroleum, mineral, or groundwater exploration or production; stratigraphic or engineering investigation).
Country (ISO 3166-1998 Codes or Geonames URIs should be used for instances of countries).
Any hole drilled into the earth for the purpose of examining the earth material into which it is drilled, excluding holes drilled for petroleum purposes.
A CO2 Emission source - including power stations, petroleum fields, gas processing plants, oil refineries, coke production plants.
Environmentally sustainable sites for CO2 injection.
The tidal mouth of a large river, where the tide meets the stream.
Permit to provide exclusive rights to undertake seismic surveys and drilling in a defined area.
A mass of rock that can be recognized by its composition, structures or fossil content and mapped on the basis of those characteristics.

Place (site) where an observation and/or measurement was made and/or sampling took place. For example observations/measurements/samples of rocks, soil, stream sediments, water, regolith, landform, vegetation, or rock properties.

The bounding polygon of a map as in, for example, the National Mapping 1:250 000 map sheet index. Mapsheets can be any scale, and include standard mapsheet boundaries and non-standard mapsheet boundaries.

Subsets of a survey, referred to as segments. Operations segments are defined by a substantial change in the recording parameters of a survey, loop segments are defined where the survey loops on itself, and sampling segments identify where the ship may have stopped or slowed for sampling.
An aggregation of mineralisation that may or may not have resources defined.
A mineralised zone may describe a zone of uneconomic mineralisation or an economic orebody. There may be one or more mineralised zone within a specific Mineral Deposit entity.
A mining operation or mineral exploration project that includes multiple mineral deposits.

This entity contains data about observatories - buildings or places set apart for, and furnished with instruments for making, observations of natural phenomena; esp., for magnetic observations, ,astronomical, meteorological.
Containers joining two connection points for the transportation of oil, gas, water or other materials.
Gazetteer (geographical index or dictionary) place names, e.g. 'Wagga Wagga  region' or 'Captains Flats'
This entity contains data about political regions and boundaries.
Harbour - a place by the sea, or by a river or other waterway, where ships and boats can dock, load, and unload.
Site where fossil fuel, nuclear, hydro, solar, wind, biological or other resources are converted into electrical power.
Licence granted to holder of exploration permit or retention lease, for the recovery of petroleum following a commercial discovery.
A GA-defined project.
The administratoriv unit 'province'.
Locality for adding value to raw materials, particularly minerals.

Proposed, planned or developing scheme, including infrastructure, for extracting resources that requires a large amount of time, effort, capital, or planning. Once developed, the type of entity could change to MINE, WELL, RESOURCE PROCESSING PLANT, or something similar.
Lease granted to holder of exploration permit, where a discovery is not currently commercial but is expected to become so.

A set of observations and/or measurements and/or samples taken at points or intervals along a line, section or traverse, in any direction at or beneath the earth's surface (measured section). For example, observations of a group of stratigraphic units or regolith zones.

Information about seismic lines for a given survey.  Each seismic line has a different name, but the parameters of seismic lines in any given segment should be similar.  A segment may consist of many lines, and a line may fall within more than 1 segment if the operating parameters change.
States and Territories of Australia
An airborn survey, usually conducted for the collection of marine, gravity or seismic data.

An actual or proposed hole in the ground, designed to exchange fluids between a subsurface reservoir and the surface (or another reservoir) or to retrieve rock core or samples or to enable the detection and measurement of rock properties.  A well (e.g. sidetrack or horizontal well) may originate from another well defined by PARENT.
Permit to conduct further exploration and/or appraisal activities within the location blocks to determine more accurately the nature of the discovery.
